# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# .gitleaksignore — per-finding secret-scan waivers
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Purpose
#   This file tells gitleaks to ignore a specific finding by its
#   fingerprint. Use it when a documented, intentional, non-secret value
#   trips a default rule (e.g., a synthetic AWS-shaped key in a test
#   fixture, or an example token embedded in user-facing documentation).
#
# Format
#   One fingerprint per line. Blank lines and lines beginning with `#`
#   are ignored. A fingerprint takes one of two shapes:
#
#     # In-tree (no-git) findings — what `gitleaks detect --no-git` emits:
#     path/to/file:rule-id:line
#
#     # History findings — what a full repo scan emits:
#     <commit-sha>:path/to/file:rule-id:line
#
#   The exact fingerprint string is printed in the JSON report under the
#   key `Fingerprint`. Copy it verbatim — gitleaks compares string-equal.
#
# Hygiene playbook (summary)
#   Every entry in this file must satisfy *all* of:
#     1. The flagged value is documented and not a real credential.
#     2. The PR that adds the entry explains why the value cannot or should
#        not be removed/redacted at source.
#     3. A code-owning reviewer (security area) approved the entry.
#     4. A comment on the entry — placed on the line immediately above —
#        names the file, the rule, and the rationale, so a future reader
#        can audit without spelunking history.
#
#   If the fixture or document the entry waives is rotated, refactored, or
#   removed, the corresponding entry here must also be deleted — stale
#   entries are a smell that the original threat-model trade-off no longer
#   applies.
#
#   The full allowlist-hygiene playbook (review cadence, who owns audits,
#   how entries are reaped) is published in
#   `docs/ci/secret-scan-allowlist.md`.
#
# When the hook fires on something you believe is a false positive
#   Do not add an entry here as your first move. Instead:
#     a. Confirm the value is not a real secret. Rotate it now if it is.
#     b. Try to remove or redact the value at source. The best waiver is
#        no waiver.
#     c. If (b) is impossible (e.g., a deliberately-shaped test fixture),
#        capture the fingerprint from the gitleaks JSON report, add it
#        here with a comment, and reference the rationale in the PR
#        description.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Entries
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# tests/fixtures/secrets/synthetic_aws_key.txt — aws-access-token
# Deliberately-shaped synthetic AWS access key used by the secret-scan
# round-trip test (`scripts/test-secret-scan.sh`). The fixture is meant
# to TRIP the upstream `aws-access-token` rule — that is the test's
# pass condition — so it cannot be removed at source. The round-trip
# test uses `--gitleaks-ignore-path` with its own temporary ignore
# files, so it does not consume this entry; this entry exists so the
# default `gitleaks detect` invocation used by `cargo xtask security`,
# the pre-commit hook, and the CI workflow stay green. Added 2026-05-14.
tests/fixtures/secrets/synthetic_aws_key.txt:aws-access-token:8
